News
Last revised: May 01, 2026
     _________________________________________________________________

                                What's new?


  This file lists major and incompatible changes in Eggdrop versions.
  You can find the full list of changes in doc/Changes1.10.
  For support, feel free to visit us on Libera #eggdrop.

  For upgrading help, read the UPGRADING file.

  In general, always make a BACKUP of your config and user/chanfile
  before performing an upgrade!

     _________________________________________________________________

devinkbrown fork (based on v1.10.1):

 Wave 76 — Python API parity, linebuf port, tclhash unification:

  Python API — 26 new commands (pycmds.c), total now 174/197 (88% parity):
    - Botnet/DCC (7): link, unlink, valididx, botlist, setdccaway, getchan,
      setchan.
    - Logging (2): putloglev, putcmdlog.
    - Matching/Utils (3): matchaddr, rfcequal, binds.
    - Channel management (14): ischanban, ischanexempt, ischaninvite,
      newchanban, newchanexempt, newchaninvite, killchanexempt,
      killchaninvite, stick, unstick, stickexempt, unstickexempt,
      stickinvite, unstickinvite.

  Python auto-source:
    - TOML [scripts] section now auto-detects .py files and routes them to
      the Python script engine, even in Tcl builds.  Previously .py files
      required the pysource Tcl command.

  linebuf port (net.c):
    - Replaced simple char *inbuf (realloc + memmove) with ophion's
      op_linebuf (slab-allocated, CRLF-aware line framing).  Inbound socket
      data is now parsed into buf_head_t via op_linebuf_parse(), with
      zero-memmove line extraction via op_linebuf_get().
    - Binary and SOCK_BUFFER modes preserved; outbound path (egg_mbuf_t)
      unchanged.

  tclhash.c unification:
    - Unified init_bind(): single table creation block with conditional func
      attachment, down from two near-identical 20-line blocks.
    - Unified check_tcl_listen(): single check_tcl_bind path for both builds.
    - Fixed bug: H_time, H_cron, H_note tables now created in no-Tcl builds
      (were previously missing, making time/cron/note binds silently no-op).
    - HAVE_TCL directives: 6 → 5.

 Wave 75 — Tcl decoupling, Python API expansion, zero-warning build:

  Tcl decoupling — complete HAVE_TCL removal:
    - All #ifdef HAVE_TCL guards removed from every application source file
      (58 files).  Functions that were previously compiled only in Tcl builds
      now compile unconditionally using lush.h stub macros (no-Tcl) or the
      real Tcl API (Tcl builds).  Dead-code paths from stubs are optimised
      away by the compiler.
    - Added 12 new lush.h stubs: Tcl_WideInt, Tcl_NewWideIntObj, Tcl_Alloc,
      Tcl_Concat, Tcl_GlobalEval, Tcl_InterpDeleted, Tcl_ServiceAll,
      Tcl_TraceVar2, Tcl_UntraceVar2, Tcl_UtfToExternalDString, and
      Tcl_VarTraceProc typedef.
    - notcl_setvar/notcl_getvar made available in both build configurations:
      in Tcl builds they delegate to Tcl_SetVar/Tcl_GetVar; in no-Tcl builds
      they walk the registered variable tables directly.  configtoml.c now
      uses these exclusively, removing its last Tcl dependency.
    - Runtime `if (interp)` checks replace compile-time #ifdef in the few
      places where Tcl-specific behaviour must be preserved (cmd_tcl,
      cmd_set, tell_verbose_status, main startup).
    - Remaining HAVE_TCL markers (19 total) are all structural/irreducible:
      lush.h (4), tcl.c (7), tclegg.h (2), tclhash.c (6).  python.mod
      retains 28 markers for the Tcl-Python bridge.

  Python API — 33 new commands (pycmds.c):
    - 8 timer commands: utimer, timer, killtimer, killutimer, timers,
      utimers, timerexists, utimerexists.
    - 25 general commands:
      User/Module: getuser, setuser, setpass, encpass, addbot, botattr,
        loadmodule, unloadmodule, modules, backup.
      DCC/Partyline: whom, dccbroadcast, boot, console, echo, dccputchan,
        getdccidle, getdccaway.
      Misc: strftime, ctime, myip, callevent, md5, dccsimul, traffic.

  Code quality — zero-warning build:
    - Eliminated all ~80 compiler warnings across 20+ files.  The build now
      compiles 134 compilation units with zero warnings on GCC 15.
    - Fixed lush.h macro stubs that generated -Wunused-value and
      -Wstatement-with-no-effect warnings: Tcl_ListObjAppendElement,
      Tcl_ListObjLength, Tcl_ListObjGetElements, Tcl_ListObjIndex,
      Tcl_DictObjPut, Tcl_GetStringFromObj, Tcl_ScanElement, Tcl_SplitList.
    - Added __attribute__((unused)) to Tcl trace handler functions across
      irc.mod, server.mod, dns.mod, and core source that are registered
      via Tcl_TraceVar (no-op in non-Tcl builds) but must exist for the
      function pointer tables.
    - Fixed -Wdiscarded-qualifiers in isupport.c (8 instances of const
      char * passed to op_free).
    - Fixed -Wcomment in chan_handlers.c (unclosed block comment).
    - Suppressed unused variable warnings in all Tcl command stubs across
      tcldcc.c, tclmisc.c, tcluser.c, tclfiles.c, tcltransfer.c,
      tclserv.c, tclisupport.c, tclirc.c.

  Feature improvements:
    - .status output now shows: scripting engines (Tcl/Python), loaded
      module count, and RSS memory usage (via getrusage).
    - Startup banner now logs: active scripting engines, feature flags
      (TLS, IPv6), and build date/time.
    - TOML config: improved error messages for missing nick/owner, warning
      when no modules are configured, config path logged on successful load.
    - .python partyline command stub (requires owner flag).
    - .set command now works in non-Tcl builds using notcl_getvar/setvar to
      read and write registered C variables directly.

 Code quality — C23 modernisation:
    - Entire codebase compiled as -std=gnu23 with -Wshadow=local enforced.
    - Loop counters and single-use variables moved to point of first use
      throughout all source files (net.c, tls.c, chanprog.c, language.c,
      share.mod, blowfish.mod, python.mod, webui.mod, irc.mod, dns.mod,
      transfer.mod, notes.mod, server.mod, channels.mod, filesys.mod,
      ident.mod, pbkdf2.mod, and all core src/ files). 55 files changed,
      net ~350 lines removed.
    - op_strbuf_t (libop dynamic string builder) wired through all string-
      construction sites replacing snprintf/strlcpy chaining.
    - libop synced from ophion: CIDR parsing helpers (op_cidr_parse_str /
      op_cidr_parse_addr) and C11 threads middle tier in thread_pool.c.

 Python API — 43 earlier commands (pycmds.c + eggtools.py):
    - Channel presence: onchan, handonchan, onchansplit, topic, validchan,
      getchanjoin, botisowner, isowner.
    - Channel modes/actions: getchanmode, pushmode, flushmode, putkick,
      resetbans, resetexempts, resetinvites, resetchan, refreshchan.
    - Ban/exempt/invite management: banlist, exemptlist, invitelist, newban,
      killban, killchanban, newexempt, killexempt, newinvite, killinvite,
      matchban, matchexempt, matchinvite, stickban, unstickban, isban,
      isexempt, isinvite.
    - User channel records: getchaninfo, setchaninfo, addchanrec, delchanrec,
      haschanrec, setlaston.
    - Server: jump.
    - irc.mod: flush_mode exported at function table slot 29 for external
      module access.
    - eggtools.py: type-annotated wrappers for all new commands, plus
      MaskEntry dataclass for ban/exempt/invite list entries.

 Tcl is now fully optional — no-Tcl builds are complete:
    - A no-Tcl build is now fully functional for core bot operation, not
      merely compile-clean.  All TOML configuration keys ([bot], [network],
      [security], [paths], [servers], [channels]) now reach their
      underlying C variables in no-Tcl builds via a new variable registry
      (notcl_setvar / notcl_getvar).  Previously these settings were
      silently discarded.
    - The variable registry works by moving def_tcl_strings/ints/coups
      (the name→C-buffer mapping tables) above the #ifdef HAVE_TCL block
      so they are compiled in both configurations.  In Tcl builds the
      tables continue to drive Tcl trace callbacks as before; in no-Tcl
      builds init_tcl1() registers them so set_tcl_var() can resolve any
      setting name to its C storage.
    - Server persistence in no-Tcl builds: add_server() and
      old_add_server() are pure C with no Tcl API calls and are no longer
      guarded by #ifdef HAVE_TCL.  old_add_server() is now exported via
      server_table[55] (server_add_str macro) so configtoml.c can call it
      directly when processing [servers] list entries.
    - Python (python.mod) is now the sole scripting engine when Tcl is
      disabled.  It registers itself automatically via script_register()
      at startup, handling all [scripts] entries from the TOML config
      without requiring any user configuration changes.

 Build system / portability changes:
    - Tcl is optional at compile time.  Build without Tcl:
        meson setup builddir/ -Dtcl=disabled && ninja -C builddir/
      Zero warnings on GCC 15.  All Tcl-only functions and declarations
      throughout the codebase are guarded with #ifdef HAVE_TCL.
      Affected modules: server.mod (server.c, servmsg.c),
      channels.mod (channels.c, cmdschan.c), filesys.mod (filedb3.c/h,
      filesys.h), irc.mod, twitch.mod, sasl, isupport, console.mod.
    - lush.h stub macros corrected: Tcl_DictObjFirst no longer produces
      a "right-hand side of comma expression has no effect" warning;
      Tcl_TraceVar and BADARGS are now proper no-op stubs.

 Bug fixes:
    - Fixed [paths] section ordering: module-registered variables (e.g.
      chanfile from channels.mod) were silently dropped when [paths]
      appeared before [modules] in the config.  All [paths] entries are
      now buffered and replayed after all modules load, so section order
      no longer matters.
    - Added [paths] lang_dir support: set lang_dir = "/path/to/language"
      to override the language file search path.  A pre-scan applies
      lang_dir before init_language(1), eliminating spurious "LANG: No
      lang files found for section core" messages in non-default-prefix
      and dev-build environments.
    - Fixed three io_uring SQPOLL bugs that prevented IRC registration
      from completing when the SQPOLL kernel thread was active:
      (1) io_uring_submit() was skipped for SQPOLL rings, so SQEs were
          written but the kernel-visible tail was never updated; the
          SQPOLL thread never saw new requests and delivered no CQEs.
      (2) Server data arriving immediately on connect (e.g. CAP LS)
          was silently overwritten: the re-arm loop called
          uring_recv_sock() even when recv_buf already held data,
          issuing a new SQE that clobbered the buffered bytes.
      (3) When buffered recv data was present but no new CQEs were
          queued, the event loop returned -3 (idle) before reaching the
          dispatch path, so the buffered bytes were never processed.
      Together these prevented the bot from receiving the server's CAP
      LS response and completing IRC registration.

 Memory and performance changes:
    - Replaced glibc malloc with an mmap-backed slab allocator (egg_bh)
      for the two hottest allocation types: memberlist nodes (one per
      channel member) and masklist nodes (bans/exempts/invites).
      Alloc/free is now O(1) with no heap fragmentation; memory is
      returned to the OS when slabs are destroyed. Exported via new
      typed functions channel_malloc_member / channel_free_member /
      channel_malloc_mask / channel_free_mask (channels_funcs[49-52]).
    - Fixed n_realloc() silently returning NULL on out-of-memory instead
      of aborting, matching the existing n_malloc() behaviour.
    - Added n_strdup() / nstrdup() with DEBUG_MEM tracking. Modules
      gain nstrdup via global[329] with correct MODULE_NAME attribution.
    - Consolidated all allocation to libop: nmalloc/nfree/nrealloc/nstrdup
      now route to op_malloc/op_free/op_realloc/op_strdup across all 60+
      source files (~750 call sites).  The legacy mem.c accounting module
      is removed; expmem() functions deleted throughout.  Module ABI
      preserved via thin wrappers at global_table slots 0, 1, 230, 329.
    - O(1) Robin Hood hash tables (op_htab) wired through the bind system:
      bind table lookup by name, bind mask lookup within each table, and
      channel member lookup by nickname all use op_htab for exact-match
      dispatch.  check_tcl_bind() fast-paths MATCH_EXACT via the hash
      table, falling back to linear scan only for wildcard/partial matches.
    - O(1) hash tables for ban/exempt/invite mask lists: both runtime
      masklists (from IRC MODE) and persistent maskrecs (from userfile)
      now carry per-channel op_htab indexes.  ismodeline(), u_equals_mask(),
      u_sticky_mask(), newmask() duplicate check, got_unban/unexempt/
      uninvite removal, and u_addban/delban/addexempt/delexempt/addinvite/
      delinvite all use O(1) hash lookup instead of O(n) linear scan.
      Wildcard-matching paths (ismasked, u_match_mask) remain linear.
    - Unified Tcl/no-Tcl bind dispatch in tclhash.c: eliminated ~600 lines
      of duplicated code by extracting 12 identical functions (memory
      helpers, GC, table management, match/flag checking) into shared
      unconditional code, unifying check_tcl_bind() with a DISPATCH macro
      that routes to trigger_bind() (Tcl) or dispatch_native() (no-Tcl),
      and adopting the Tcl-path check_tcl_* helpers for both builds (works
      because lush.h maps Tcl_SetVar to egg_setvar in no-Tcl mode).  Fixed
      several no-Tcl bind dispatch bugs uncovered during unification:
      check_tcl_chjn matched on wrong field, check_tcl_chpt used wrong
      match type, check_tcl_dcc was missing BIND_QUIT handling.

 twitch.mod changes:
    - Replaced fixed 8191-byte mods, vips, badges, and emote_sets
      buffers with dynamic char * fields. Each twitchchan_t previously
      consumed ~40 KB of RSS at startup regardless of channel state and
      silently truncated large mod or VIP lists at 8190 bytes. Memory is
      now allocated on first update and released on module unload.
      twitch_expmem() now reports actual live usage.

 DNS changes:
    - Replaced EGG_TDNS (threaded pthreads DNS resolver) with the
      Ophion lightweight async DNS resolver (res.c) as the sole DNS
      engine.  All DNS lookups now go through a single non-blocking UDP
      socket driven by the existing event loop.  The 'tdns' build option
      has been removed; there is no longer a background DNS thread.
    - Added DNS-over-TLS (DoT, RFC 7858) support in the dns module.
      When TLS is built in, enable via Tcl:
        dnsdot on 1.1.1.1           — Cloudflare port 853, verify cert
        dnsdot on 9.9.9.9 853       — Quad9, explicit port
        dnsdot on ::1 853 -noverify — self-signed cert, no verify
        dnsdot off                  — revert to plain UDP
        dnsdot                      — report current status
      RFC 7858 framing (2-byte length prefix) is handled internally with
      a reassembly buffer so partial TLS records are never lost.
      Automatic reconnect retries the DoT server after a configurable
      delay if the TLS session is lost.

 IRC module changes:
    - Added IRCX/Ophion protocol support.  When net_type = "Ophion" the
      bot automatically negotiates IRCX mode (RPL_IRCX 800), handles +q
      (channel owner) in mode parsing, and supports the CREATE, PROP, and
      ACCESS IRCX commands.  New Tcl commands: ircxprop, ircxaccess,
      ircxcreate, ircxautoowner, ircxnegotiate, botisowner, isowner.
      New DCC command: .create <#channel> [modes].  OWNERKEY credentials
      are persisted to the channel file and restored on restart.  A new
      [ircx] config section documents all Ophion-specific settings and
      Tcl bind points.
    - Added allow_hello and allow_addhost config settings (in [irc]).
      Setting either to 0 globally disables the corresponding MSG command.
      Previously users had to add "unbind msg …" Tcl to the config.

 Configuration changes:
    - Added TOML configuration format as a modern alternative to the
      traditional Tcl-script config. Files with a .toml extension are
      parsed automatically; no chmod u+x is required.
    - Automatic userfile creation on first run: when owner = "Nick,…" is
      set in the config and no user file exists, the bot creates the user
      file automatically and adds each listed handle as an owner
      (USER_MASTER | USER_OWNER).  The -m flag is no longer required for
      new installs using TOML.  Connect via DCC or .tcl to set passwords.
    - Added per-channel settings via [[chanset]] TOML array-of-table
      blocks.  Each block configures one channel: all 26 boolean flags
      (autoop, bitch, cycle, protectops, etc.) accept true/false values
      which are dispatched as +/- prefix to "channel set"; valued options
      (chanmode, idle_kick, flood_chan, ban_time, need_op, etc.) are set
      directly.  IRCX ownerkey/ircx_create/ircx_create_modes keys are
      handled per-channel and emitted as ircxautoowner calls.
    - Added interactive first-time setup wizard: run `eggdrop --setup`
      (or `eggdrop -s [output.toml]`) to walk through a five-step
      guided flow and generate a ready-to-use TOML config:
        Step 1 — Bot identity: nick (required), altnick/realname/
          username/filenames derived automatically from the nick.
        Step 2 — IRC server: network-type menu (Libera/EFnet/IRCnet/
          Undernet/DALnet/QuakeNet/Rizon/Other) with per-network
          default hostnames; editable port (6697 SSL / 6667 plain);
          optional server password.  SASL sub-step offered when SSL is
          enabled: mechanism menu (PLAIN/EXTERNAL/SCRAM-SHA-256/
          SCRAM-SHA-512), username/password prompts.
        Step 3 — Channels: up to 8 channels; first required, validated
          for '#' prefix; subsequent channels collected until empty.
        Step 4 — Files: user/chan/log filenames, defaults from nick.
        Step 5 — Optional modules: notes/seen/transfer/filesys.
        Summary table printed before writing; write-to-disk confirmation.
      The generated config now covers every section and setting:
      [modules], [bot], [servers], [channels] with all default_* values,
      [[chanset]], [paths], [logging], [irc] with advanced options,
      [network], [security], [behaviour], [sasl], [ctcp], [ircx],
      [share], [dns], [notes], [transfer], [filesys], [console],
      [crypto], and [tcl].  No 'chmod u+x' required.
    - Shipped eggdrop-basic.toml as the human-friendly TOML counterpart
      to eggdrop-basic.conf. Both formats are fully supported and can
      coexist; existing .conf files continue to work unchanged.
    - Full TOML↔Tcl setting parity: all 128+ Tcl variables from
      eggdrop.conf are now present in eggdrop.toml. Naming bugs fixed:
        · [ssl] capath → ssl_capath (sets Tcl var ssl-capath)
        · [console] console_flags → console (sets Tcl var console)
        · [ssl] ssl_verify_depth → ssl_chain_depth (Tcl: ssl-chain-depth)
        · [irc] duplicate default_port removed (already in [network])
      Missing settings added: [irc] server_cycle_wait, server_timeout,
      keep_nick, quiet_reject, flood_msg, flood_ctcp, account_notify,
      extended_join, cap_request, away_notify, invite_notify,
      message_tags, account_tag, firewall, modes_per_line, kick_method,
      include_lk, rfc_compliant, use_354, invite_key, max_bans,
      max_exempts, max_invites, max_modes, check_mode_r, use_penalties,
      use_fastdeq, init_server, connect_server, stackable_commands,
      stackable2_commands; [channels] all default_* flood/ban/exempt/
      invite/stopnethack/revenge settings; [behaviour] use_telnet_banner,
      force_expire, share_greet; new [sasl] section with all eight SASL
      mechanism fields; new [ctcp] section (ctcp_version/finger/userinfo);
      new [share] section (allow_resync, resync_time, private_global,
      private_user, override_bots, private_globals, share_compressed);
      new [dns] section (dns_maxsends, dns_retrydelay, dns_cache,
      dns_negcache, dns_servers); new [ircx] section for Ophion settings.
    - Added Tcl code-block support: [tcl] code = """...""" (triple-
      quoted multi-line string) is evaluated as a single Tcl_Eval()
      call, ideal for proc definitions and bind chains.  The parser now
      detects incomplete triple-quoted values and accumulates continuation
      lines before evaluating, the same way it already handled inline
      arrays.  Both eggdrop.toml and eggdrop-basic.toml document the
      feature with a commented example.
    - Fixed silent HTTP response truncation in the webui module: the
      snprintf calls for 404, 200-OK, and 101-Upgrade responses were
      passing sizeof(char*) (pointer size = 8) instead of the actual
      allocated buffer length, truncating all responses to 7 characters.

 Build system changes:
    - Replaced autoconf/make with Meson + Ninja. See INSTALL for the new
      quick-start instructions. All platforms (Linux, macOS, Windows,
      Cygwin) are supported via a single meson setup / ninja workflow.
    - Build now defaults to optimisation level 2 and passes -pipe where
      the compiler supports it.
    - LTO (Link-Time Optimization) enabled by default (b_lto=true) for
      cross-file inlining and dead-code elimination. assert() is stripped
      in release builds (b_ndebug=if-release).
    - Added -fno-strict-aliasing globally: eggdrop uses void*/char* casts
      that technically violate strict-aliasing rules; disabling the
      optimization prevents undefined behaviour from being compiled away.
    - Added -Wl,--as-needed on ELF platforms: only libraries that are
      actually referenced are linked, reducing startup time and avoiding
      spurious dlopen dependencies.
    - Added native-opt build option (default on): pass
      -Dnative-opt=false to meson to disable CPU tuning; by default
      running the build. Flag selected automatically by architecture:
      -march=native on x86/x86_64/RISC-V/MIPS/s390x, -mcpu=native on
      ARM/AArch64/PowerPC (sets core type and tune in one flag).
      Non-portable; not for distribution builds.
    - Module shared objects now built with -fvisibility=hidden so that
      all internal symbols are private. Module entry points are marked
      with EXPORT_SCOPE which expands to
      __attribute__((visibility("default"))) on GCC/Clang ELF targets
      and __declspec(dllexport) on Cygwin/Windows.
    - Removed unneeded Tcl and OpenSSL dependencies from the MD5 static
      library; md5c.c only uses <string.h> and has no Tcl/TLS code.
    - Deduplicated -DDEBUG/-g: these flags are now applied once via
      add_project_arguments() rather than being duplicated into each
      per-target c_args list.

 Platform changes:
    - macOS, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, and NetBSD use the kqueue backend
      (inherited from upstream v1.10.1) for efficient event-driven I/O.
      None of these platforms fall back to select().
    - Added native Windows support (MinGW-w64 and MSVC). The bot
      compiles and links against Winsock2/MsWSock with no Cygwin layer
      required. Module loading uses LoadLibrary/GetProcAddress.
    - Added IOCP (I/O Completion Ports) backend for native Windows builds,
      using zero-byte overlapped WSARecv/WSASend to arm readiness
      notifications — the Windows equivalent of epoll/kqueue.
      Implementation adapted from libop (https://github.com/devinkbrown/ophion),
      the I/O layer of the ophion project by the same author. libop was
      chosen because it had already solved the hard parts in
      production-tested C: safe OVERLAPPED-first-member casting, stale
      completion detection after socket close, and per-slot double-arm
      prevention. Adapting proven code avoided reimplementing those
      failure modes from scratch inside Eggdrop.
    - I/O backend priority chain is now: io_uring → epoll → kqueue →
      IOCP → select(). Each backend is auto-detected at configure time.
      Every major platform has a native, scalable backend; select() is
      the last-resort fallback for Cygwin and unknown platforms only.
    - Removed CYGWIN_HACKS. Cygwin still compiles on the plain POSIX
      path (select() fallback) and is unaffected by the Windows changes.
    - On native Windows the bot always runs in the foreground; the
      console window is hidden via ShowWindow() instead of fork().

 Python scripting changes:
    - TCL is now an optional build dependency.  Build without Tcl using
      `meson setup -Dtcl=disabled builddir` and the bot uses Python as
      its sole scripting engine.  All TOML [scripts] entries are loaded
      via python.mod's script_load() function.
    - Expanded the eggdrop Python C API (python.mod) with 30+ new
      functions covering the full range of TCL scripting features:
        · Channel member status: isop, ishalfop, isvoice, isaway,
          botisop, botishalfop, botisvoice
        · IRC account / handle resolution: getaccount, nick2hand,
          hand2nick, isbotnick
        · User database: countusers, validuser, finduser, userlist
        · Miscellaneous: rand, unixtime, duration, maskhost
        · Server queues: puthelp, tagmsg
        · IRCv3: cap (req/raw)
        · IRCX/Ophion: ircxprop, ircxaccess, ircxcreate, ircxnegotiate
    - Added scripts/eggtools.py — a modern Python utility library that
      replaces the functionality of the legacy alltools.tcl for Python
      script authors.  Key features:
        · Type-annotated wrappers for the full eggdrop C API
        · @on_pub, @on_msg, @on_join … decorator-based bind registration
        · Member dataclass for channel member introspection
        · every() helper for interval-based callbacks using the cron bind
        · IRCX and IRCv3 helpers (ircxprop, ircxaccess, cap_req, tagmsg)
        · alltools.tcl-compatible aliases: putmsg, putchan, putnotc,
          putact, strlwr, strupr, strlen, strcmp, stricmp
        · Utility functions: randstring, ordnumber, isnumber, testip,
          hostmatch, duration, maskhost
    - All bind tables (pub, msg, join, part, kick, mode, nick, sign,
      notc, ctcp, ctcr, raw, time, cron, dcc, evnt, and all server.mod
      and irc.mod tables) are pre-created in no-Tcl builds so that
      Python binds registered via eggdrop.bind() fire correctly.

 Documentation changes:
    - INSTALL completely rewritten for the Meson build system with
      per-platform dependency installation steps (Debian/Ubuntu, Fedora,
      macOS Homebrew, MSYS2/MinGW-w64, MSVC/vcpkg, Cygwin).
    - README updated with fork notice, new build instructions, and the
      full I/O backend table.

     _________________________________________________________________

Eggdrop v1.10.1:

 General changes:
    - Added kqueue I/O back-end for macOS, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, and NetBSD,
      replacing the select() fallback with an efficient event-driven
      interface that scales with the number of active (not total) sockets
    - Added a new SCRAM authentication method for SASL
    - Fixed an issue where the bot can crash if the bot parts while the
      channel memberlist is not yet synched
    - Removed TLS commands deprecated by openssl 3.0
    - Fixed a 1.10.0 bug where userhost-in-names was always used if offered by
      the server, even if the bot did not request it
    - Account changes are now logged under the +j console flag, not the +k
      console flag
    - Fixed a bug handling long server or password strings in .jump
    - Fixed a possible crash condition if a bot is marked as away
    - Added compatibility for a change by inspircd adding extra :s to for all
      trailing commands
    - Fixed a bug where putlog timestamps may be off by a second
    - Add notice of expired TLS certs at startup and owner login
    - Fixed malformed content in the language files

 Botnet changes:
    - Added a check to ensure TLS handshake is complete before testing/writing
      to socket, eliminating many of those annoying "dequeue_sockets():
      errno = 11 (Resource temporarily unavailable) on 7" log messages during
      botnet linking

 Tcl API changes:
    - Added a new CHANSET bind, allowing users to trigger Tcl procs when a
      a channel setting is modified
    - Removed a non-casesensitive comparison for non-stacked binds that
      prevented proc names from being overwritten
    - Fixed an issue with utimers ignoring the [count] argument
    - Fixed an issue where calling a bind log improperly clears the Tcl
      interpreter result, causing issues with subsequent processing

 Module changes:
    - Removed python.mod's reliance on IRC mod, thereby preventing a crash
      condition when unloaded (such as on a .restart)
    - Similar to .tcl, the .python command now requires the owner flag
    - Fixed a bug in the python module where storage was not properly segmented
      by threads
    - Fixed a bug introduced in 1.9.4 where unloading the IRC module caused a
      crash
    - Fixed an issue with PBKDF2 where it did not properly 'make' on certain
      systems (such as NetBSD)

 Eggdrop config changes:
    - Added "SCRAM-SHA-512" SASL authentication method to config

 Documentation changes:
    - Added python script tutorial
    - Added documentation for SASL SCRAM mode
    - Fixed userfile tutorial formatting
    - Fixed utimers description to specify the return value is seconds, not
      minutes
    - Updated Cygwin install requirements

     _________________________________________________________________

Eggdrop v1.10.0:

 General changes:
    - Added the new Tcl 'autoscripts' capability. By loading the autoscripts Tcl
      script, Eggdrop can automatically view, download and install Tcl scripts
      hosted by the Eggheads team, all via the partyline! No modification of the
      config file needed.
    - Eggdrop can now use the account a user is logged into as an identification
      method in the same manner that a hostmask does. For this feature to be
      fully accurate, Eggdrop use a server with WHOX enabled and negotiate the
      extended-join and account-notify IRCv3 capabilities.
    - Added the IRCv3 userhost-in-names capability. This capability is
      negotiated with the server at connect and prompts the server to add
      hostmask to the NAMES command. This is useful in a scenario where an IRC
      server has disabled the WHO command, but allows 
      Eggdrop to still track hostmasks (and removes the "pending" status from
      the channel listing under .status).
    - Added the IRCv3 standard-replies capability. This capability is negotiated
      with the server at connect and enables the use of non-numeric FAIL, WARN,
      and NOTE messages.
    - Modified .bans to properly display channel bans.
    - Fixed a bug with network reads performed on TLS connections, where
      Eggdrop could hang until a connection times out, most commonly
      manifesting itself on server connects and userfile transfers. This is
      expected to fix the last documented issue with Eggdrop's handling of
      secure connections.
    - Eggdrop now requires TLS/SSL libs to be installed by default. Whereas
      previously Eggdrop would previously continue to compile if TLS libraries
      were not found, it will now error unless the user explicitly specifies
      the --disable-tls flag.
    - Fixed the Monitor bind to properly use wildcards in binds.
    - Updated language files from ISO-8859 to UTF-8.

 Botnet changes:
    - Fixed an issue in pbkdf2-only links properly using/comparing PASS2 entries

 Tcl API changes:
    - Updated much of the core Tcl integration to be compatible with the
      upcoming Tcl 9 release. Much work was done (thank you DasBrain!) to update
      Eggdrop's internal Tcl calls to prevent breakages using Tcl 9. Most of
      these changes are transparent to the user, but the one major item to call
      out is the improvement of Tcl's UTF-8 emoji handling, which no longer
      requires users to modify TCL_MAX and compile Tcl manually in order to use
      emojis properly.
    - The Python module (below) adds the pysource Tcl command, to load
      a python script into Eggdrop.
    - Added the Tcl CHGHOST bind, which is triggered when a user's
      hostmask is changed via an IRCv3 CHGHOST message.
    - Added the 'hidden-host' type to the event (EVNT) bind. This bind
      is triggered when the bot's own host is hidden (+x) by a 396
      message sent by server.
    - Added the 'got-chanlist' type to the event (EVNT) bind. This bind
      is triggered once Eggdrop finishes receiving the list of usernames
      for a channel from a server. This can be used when Eggdrop needs to
      wait to perform specific functions when joining a channel but
      needs to wait until the users on a channel have been presented by
      the server. 
    - Fixed a bug in the isidentified command to check if a user has
      definitively been identified or unidentified.

 Module changes:
    - Added a Python module! This module integrates an embedded Python
      interpreter similar to the Tcl interpreter already present in
      Eggdrop. This module adds the .python command to the partyline
      (again, similar to the .tcl command) to execute python strings,
      as well as adding the pysource Tcl command that will load a Python
      script into Eggdrop. See doc/modules/mod.python for details on how
      to use it, or example scripts in the scripts/ directory.

 Eggdrop config changes:
    - The copy-to-tmp option was removed from the config. This value is
      now functions under the old '1' behavior where an intermediate temp
      file is created before copying from/to files that are in use.
    - The quick-logs option was removed from the config. This value was
      created to hedge against frequent writes to disk, but is less
      relveant with today's technology. Eggdrop now writes logfiles to
      disk immediately.
    - The old DNS module section was removed
    - A Python module section was added, but does not load the python
      module by default.
    - The Autoscripts capability to load and manage some scripts from the
      partyline is loaded by default

 Documentation changes:
    - Added documentation that covers values commonly used when writing
      new Tcl binds in C
    - Added a tutorial to demonstrate how to share userfiles
    - Added version variable for document generation
